caption: Cute Bushwick spot with light tasty drinks made mostly with sparkling wine. Nice staff, great Ramen, dumplings and pineapple fried rice!! Seating indoors and out and I appreciated the hand sanitizer on every table.

HOWEVER their service was pretty awesome especially when I happened to be there while it started pouring rain to the point it didn't matter the outdoor dining areas were covered like everyone was soaking wet but they honestly handled it all like amazingly considering most places these days cant handle confused customers trying to order just unsure since every single place is different but the only common denominator is there's some weird ordering way or thing in place just you don't know what it is lol maybe theres a special place they order and then wait? or find a QR code and/or go online to order? find a small paper taped up with the menu and how to order in a font size 10 or smaller expected to be read by everyone and seen? or simply and also the most obvious one - being telepathic and sending your order/asking questions to anyone working via both of your telepathic mind control powers? so not only did this place totally not do that LIKE EVERY OTHER PLACE AROUND THERE but really killed it at customer service and went above and beyond for a ton of people depending on each situation whether it was take out, dining outside and getting rained on etc - it was noticeable and much appreciated so kudos to the entire staff because every single person working there was SO nice and would attempt to help or immediately find someone who could. super attentive in a good way. food was lacking .. a lot. maybe I'm just not a fan of pan asian restaurants like that? but I kinda knew what I was getting into before ordering the second I saw the glossy picture filled menu that looked like something from a chile's or like fridays etc type chain lol thanks again to the staff there that night - you guys were great and deserve to know it and compliments on that :)

Went here on a double date so my rating is representative of the overall experience we just had, not my sole experience!  Pros: hostess had a free table near the door (drafty and cold), but had the foresight to clear off one closer to the back so we could sit there without us even saying anything! It’s really lovely when staff thinks ahead, and never expected. The food was tasty as well, and the prices were totally fair.  Cons: right off the bat, the server told us they were out of two key proteins on the menu. I can understand 86’s happen, but to be missing two entire proteins? Our meat eating friends weren’t thrilled. The other things are very small - asked for hot oil and got a paste (just a heads up would have avoided any annoyance), and the tomato slice in my ramen had a huge, brown, hard core in the center. I totally understand not wanting to waste the tops of tomatoes but please at least cut out the inedible part! Broth was a bit weak also — to be fair, I asked for vegetable broth when their staple is fish, but it still should have been richer.  I’d be happy to come here again.

I have adored Dock since it opened, but last night I brought my mother and she ordered the seafood ramen. She hated it, but she can be picky, so I tried it. It was honestly pretty gross. Super fishy, and unappetizing. The server (who was great) took it away from the table while the rest of us ate.  We got 10 sushi rolls, and 3 tonkatsu ramen aside from that with the intention to bring things home for later. So when we got the bill and saw that the seafood ramen was still on it, my mom complained. I've been a server for the last 7 years, so I KNOW how annoying that is, but she was paying. Mind you, she ate absolutely none of it, and they took the whole bowl away untouched. In my experience, if we take food away at the customer's request untouched, we take it off the bill. Anyway, the owner/manager came over and started arguing with her. He had the gall to say that we ordered too much food! So rude!  I'm pretty torn. The food is usually good and it's been our favorite date spot, but to comment on how much food we ordered was gross. I really don't know if we'll go back.  Idk. Dock Asian Eatery is a beautiful spacious restaurant in Bushwick. They serve Japanese and Thai food with ease and grace.  The staff was gracious and so attentive. The bar was beautiful. We sat upstairs in a loft dining area. It felt like you were in exotic treehouse, dining in the tropics.  We shared the following.  Drinks: Sapparo draft beer, iced green tea and Echigo stout. The stout was refreshing and had a hint of coffee.  Sashimi special- this was so good and fresh. Esp for a restaurant serving both Thai and Japanese food. Reading the reviews, people complained about the quality of the fish. There were no complaints here.  The salmon was fatty and unctuous. The yellow tail was fresh. The tomago was soft and melted in our mouths. The scallop was sweet and so tender (this was my favorite piece). The botanical ebi head was creamy and fried to a great crunch. The otoro was very creamy and satisfying.  The chirashi bowl- this was also fresh! And the sushi rice had bits of sweet pickled vegetables and mushrooms to add texture to the rice! I liked the lean tuna, the shrimp and the salmon roe.  The seafood ramen was good- very rich flavors. I loved the added poach egg. The noodles were springy. The shrimps were good, the clams were plump but the broth was a little salty.  Chiang Mai noodles- this was slightly spicy sweet curried noodles (a version of Kaho Soi). I love the noodles! The curry was good, slightly sweet from coconut milk. The chicken chunks were a little overcooked and dry.  Beef Yakitori- good chunks of beef. It was a little dry but very flavorful.  Toro pork (pork belly)- This was the best Yakitori. The juicy crispy pork belly went perfectly with the yuzu pepper paste. This was a wonderful amazing mind blowing bite!  Shiitake Yakitori- this had a smoky flavor. It was a little undercooked and dried.  Dessert:  Coffee Jelly- concentrated coffee jelly topped with vanilla and coffee ice cream. The coffee tasted like nitro drip. It was very strong. It tasted like an affogato but with totally different textures.  Anmitsu Parfait- this had chewy delicious mochi with corn flakes, vanilla ice cream, red bean paste and topped with brown sugar syrup. This was my favorite dessert! I loved the mochi and all the blends of textures and varying levels of sweetness.  Matcha Mousse- green tea on the outside, vanilla mousse on the inside and paired with an adorable mouse-like yuzu sorbet with a mint leaf as its ears. This was my 2nd fav dessert.  This was an great meal with varying flavors and strengths. I would definitely reorder the Sashimi special, the Toro pork Yakitori, the anmitsu parfait and the matcha mousse.  @snackchatnyc
